The problem asks us to prove the existence of positive integers $b$ and $N$ such that for all $m, n$ with $n > m \ge N$, $|\sum_{j=m+1}^n (a_j - b)| \le 1007^2$.
We define $f(j) = j + a_j$. The injectivity condition implies the values $f(j)$ are distinct.
Let $S = \{f(j) \mid j \ge 1\}$. We define $H = \{x \in \mathbb{Z}_{\ge 1} \mid x \notin S\}$ as the set of "holes".
We first show that $H$ is finite. Since $1 \le a_j \le C=2015$, we have $j+1 \le f(j) \le j+C$.
Counting the number of elements in $S \cap \{1, \dots, y\}$ for large $y$, we see that there are roughly $y-C$ to $y-1$ elements, implying the number of holes is bounded.
Let $b = |H|$. Since $f(j) \ge 2$, $1 \in H$, so $b \ge 1$.
Let $N$ be such that $H \subseteq \{1, \dots, N\}$.
For $n \ge N$, the set $S$ contains all integers in $(n, \infty)$.
We analyze the partial sums $P_n = \sum_{j=1}^n (a_j - b)$ and show that $P_n$ can be written as $\Delta_n + K$ where $\Delta_n$ is bounded.
